      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1580">
               <p>Pawson, a native of <placeName>Thorner</placeName>, near
                     <placeName>Leeds</placeName>, encountered Methodism in
                     <placeName>Hull</placeName> while apprenticing as a builder. He was proposed as
                  an <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerant preacher</seg> in <date when="1762">1762</date>
                  and assigned to the <placeName>York</placeName> circuit (see <hi rend="italic"
                     >Works</hi>, 10:294) and served faithfully from that point. In <date
                     when="1785">1785</date> he was ordained by <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> for the work in
                     <placeName>Scotland</placeName>, but then told to discontinue offering the
                  sacrament when he returned to <placeName>England</placeName> in <date when="1787"
                     >1787</date>. He served as President of Conference twice in the years after
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s death.
                  See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 860–61; <hi rend="italic">EMP</hi>, 4:1–108; <hi
                     rend="italic">Minutes</hi> (post-Wesley), <date when="1806">1806</date>, 2:324;
                  and Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 267–68.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
